description:
## Why

Embedders that serve multiple workspaces (e.g. oqto backend handling many users/projects) cannot use the current trx-core library cleanly because UnifiedStore::open() / Store::open() / CrdtStore::open() walk up from std::env::current_dir() to find .trx. That forces either chdir per request (kills concurrency, not async-safe) or shelling out to the trx CLI per request (~90ms/call subprocess + CRDT load on every invocation).

Concretely: oqto currently spawns trx as a child process for every list/create/update/close call from the UI sidebar, which dominates the Loading tasks... latency. With an explicit-root constructor, oqto could call trx-core directly from spawn_blocking for ~ms-level response.

## Ask

Add open_at(root: PathBuf) constructors that take an explicit repo root instead of probing the CWD:

- crdt_store.rs::CrdtStore::open_at(root) -> Result<Self>
- store.rs::Store::open_at(root) -> Result<Self>
- unified_store.rs::UnifiedStore::open_at(root) -> Result<Self>

Existing open() stays as-is (CWD-probing convenience for the CLI). Both constructors share the load() implementation; open_at just skips find_root and validates that root.join(.trx) exists, returning Error::NotInitialized otherwise.

## Sketch

```rust
// CrdtStore
pub fn open_at(root: PathBuf) -> Result<Self> {
    if !root.join(TRX_DIR).exists() {
        return Err(Error::NotInitialized);
    }
    let mut store = Self { root, issues: HashMap::new() };
    store.load()?;
    Ok(store)
}

// UnifiedStore
pub fn open_at(root: PathBuf) -> Result<Self> {
    let config = Config::load(&root.join(TRX_DIR).join(CONFIG_FILE))?;
    match config.storage_version {
        StorageVersion::V1 => Ok(UnifiedStore::V1(Store::open_at(root)?)),
        StorageVersion::V2 => Ok(UnifiedStore::V2(CrdtStore::open_at(root)?)),
    }
}
```

Roughly ~25 lines total. No behavior change for the CLI, no new deps.

## Open question / follow-up

Is V1 (single issues.jsonl) still supported intentionally, or can we drop it? V2 is the default and all current users are on V2. Dropping V1 would remove the unified_store enum split and simplify open_at to a single impl. If we keep V1, open_at lands as drafted above. If we drop V1 in a follow-up, this issue still ships first as a non-breaking addition.
